article.description: Kara Lawson and Shyra Ely each scored 16 points as No. 4 Tennessee beat Southern California 71-39 Saturday at the Forum.
article.headline: Tennessee wins fifth straight over Southern California
article.linkText: Lady Vols gain composure, rout USC
article.story:
INGLEWOOD, Calif. (AP) -- After a sluggish start, Tennessee (No. 5 ESPN/USA Today, No. 4 AP)
pulled away for yet another rout Saturday, holding Southern
California to its lowest point total in team history.

Kara Lawson and Shyra Ely each scored 16 points in a 71-39
victory, the seventh time this season the Lady Vols (7-1) have won
by at least 22.

Tennessee opened the second half by outscoring Southern
California, 14-4, increasing its lead to 42-18 with 16:02 left. The
Lady Vols would later have two 6-0 runs and a 7-0 run and led by at
least 22 for the remainder of the game. Tennessee held its biggest
lead, 34, four times.

The Women of Troy led early before Tennessee took the lead for
good 11:29 before halftime as Ashley Robinson's lay-up completed a
7-0 run.

"We had some ugly basketball out there early," Lady Vols coach
Pat Summitt said. "The team was frustrated at first. I felt that
if we could keep our composure that we would get some good shots.
The good outweighed the bad as the game went on."

Southern California was held to two points over the final 11:01
of the first half.

 The Lady Vols scored the last four points of the half on baskets
by Lawson and Loree Moore for a 28-14 halftime lead.

The 14 points were the fewest ever in a half for the Women of
Troy. The previous low was 15 in a Jan. 27, 1990 game against
Oregon State.

"It may have been a mistake to schedule this many tough games
in such a short time frame," said Southern California coach Chris
Gobrecht, whose team was facing a Top 10 school for the fourth time
in four weeks and lost all four games. "We have not been able to
recover emotionally from these losses. We are running on empty out
there. We are just not at Tennessee's level yet."

Southern California's previous low was 40 points in a March 1,
1990 game against Washington, then coached by Gobrecht.

Ebony Hoffman led the Women of Troy with 10 points. She was
taken to USC University Hospital following the game for a CAT scan
after being elbowed in the nose late in the second half.

Gwen Jackson, the Lady Vols' leading scorer with a 19.6 average
entering Saturday's play was held to two points in 15 minutes,
making one of four shots.

The win was Tennessee's fifth straight over the Trojans, giving
it an 8-7 lead in the series.

The Lady Vols have outscored their opponents by an average of
35.2 points per game.
